1.2 Show Your Code

In this final assignment, I am showing my code, as should you.

But note that I making some use of options in my YAML that hide my code by default for a nicer looking presentation. Make sure to pay attention to this YAML code block for proper indentation.

---
  html_document:
    number_sections: yes
    theme: default
    toc: yes
    code_folding: hide
---

In a portfolio for a potential employer, or an organization for which you are working, it might make sense to completely hide your code.

1.6 What are the particular predictors, or consequences that you will be investigating?

  • I do not have formal criteria for how many predictors or consequences you investigate but I imagine that a total of 2 (e.g.2 predictors, 2 consequences, or 1 predictor + 1 consequence) would work well.
  • This diagram was made in R, and I can share the code. Your diagram could be made in PowerPoint.
library(DiagrammeR) # library for making diagrams

# I use the graphViz syntax
# described here
# http://rich-iannone.github.io/DiagrammeR/graphviz_and_mermaid.html

# making diagrams can be tricky, 
# but you can use the code below as a template
# AND
# I am happy to help you tweak / troubleshoot your syntax

grViz("

digraph {

rankdir = LR

node [shape = oval, fontname = Helvetica fontsize = 10]

predictor1 -> outcome 

predictor2 -> outcome

outcome -> consequence1

outcome -> consequence2

}

")

2 Data

2.1 Data source

In this example, I am using the iris data set. It is a data set about flowers. The Iris data set was collected by Edgar Anderson.

  • Who collected your data? When?
  • How many people, or objects, are in your data?
  • Where are they from?
data(iris)

3 R

3.1 Base R graph

plot(iris$Petal.Length, # x variable
     iris$Petal.Width, # y variable
     main = "Do Flowers With Longer Petals Have Wider Petals?", # title
     xlab = "Petal Length", # x label
     ylab = "Petal Width", # y label
     pch = 19, # Plot CHaracter, 19 is filled dots
     col = "darkgreen") # color

3.2 ggplot2 graph

ggplot(iris,
       aes(x = Petal.Length, # x variable
           y = Petal.Width, # y variable
           shape = Species, # group variable
           color = Species)) + # group variable
  geom_point() + # GEOMetry
  labs(title = "Do Flowers With Longer Petals Have Wider Petals?") # title
